{"legislative_session": "2025A", "identifier": "SB25-322", "title": "Management of Consumer Protection Claims Critical Infrastructure", "from_organization": "~{\"classification\": \"upper\"}", "classification": ["bill"], "subject": [], "abstracts": [{"note": "summary", "abstract": "The bill establishes an exemption from Colorado's \"Consumer Repair Bill of Rights Act\" (Act) for information technology equipment if the equipment meets certain criteria, such as whether:\n\n\nThe equipment qualifies as critical infrastructure, as defined by federal law;\nThe equipment is sold in a retail setting or only through business-to-business or business-to-government transactions; and\nDissemination of the parts, documentation, embedded software, firmware, or tools required for the equipment would pose a security risk.\n\n\nThe attorney general may adopt rules for manufacturers of information technology equipment to submit requests for an exemption from the Act.\n\nThe bill clarifies the attorney general's responsibility regarding  discovery requests during the litigation on behalf of the state of Colorado or on behalf of the people of the state of Colorado of claims brought by the attorney general .\n(Note: Italicized words indicate new material added to the original summary; dashes through words indicate deletions from the original summary.)\n(Note: This summary applies to the reengrossed version of this bill as introduced in the second house.)"}], "other_titles": [], "other_identifiers": [], "actions": [{"description": "House Committee on Finance Refer Unamended to House Committee of the Whole", "date": "2025-05-06T06:00:00+00:00", "organization_id": "~{\"classification\": \"lower\"}", "classification": ["committee-passage", "referral-committee"], "related_entities": [{"name": "House Committee of the Whole", "entity_type": "organization", "organization_id": null}, {"name": "Finance", "entity_type": "organization", "organization_id": null}]}, {"description": "Introduced In Hou